## Build Phases

Execute in order. Each phase must compile, pass tests at 80% coverage, and pass the subagent review loop before proceeding.

### Phase 0: Environment Setup

Create monorepo structure. Initialize all 5 Next.js apps (frons-fe-main, frons-chat-main, frons-card-main, frons-admin-main, frons-j-fe). Initialize Anchor workspace. Set up Supabase project with migrations 001-024. Configure shared Tailwind theme with FRONS colors and DM Sans. Configure shared Privy auth across all apps. Verify all apps compile and run on their respective ports.

After completing, spawn Jon Skeet subagent to review project structure, dependency versions, and shared config.

### Phase 1: Database Layer

Run all 24 Supabase migrations. Verify RLS policies. Test search_articles function with sample data across all 3 tiers (DOCI exact, FTS, ILIKE). Test spend_credits and add_credits atomic functions — verify no race conditions under concurrent calls. Test check_gas_budget and spend_gas. Seed platform_settings. Write integration tests for all SQL functions.

After tests pass, spawn Jon Skeet subagent (no UI, skip Jony Ive).

### Phase 2: Smart Contract

Implement all 10 instructions in the Fronsciers Anchor program. Write BanksClient tests. Test: submission fee split math exactness — for $50 USDC (50_000_000) verify 20_000_000 to platform, 15_000_000 to pool, 5_000_000 to author, 10_000_000 to reserve, sum equals original. Test citation split: for $0.01 (10_000) verify 4_000 platform, 2_000 author, 2_000 pool, 2_000 reserve. Test rounding: remainder goes to platform. Test manuscript lifecycle: submit → review → publish → cite. Test claim_earnings. Test manage_protocol admin controls. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn Jon Skeet subagent (no UI, skip Jony Ive).

### Phase 3: MCP Server

Implement FastMCP server with all 6 tools. Implement FastAPI REST layer with x402 paywall. Implement evidence_cascade.py with all 4 tiers. Write unit tests with PubMed/Scopus APIs mocked. Test: search returns results, abstract is free, cite_and_access triggers payment, cascade falls through tiers correctly, honest admission when no sources found. Test credit charging: 3 base + 1 per Fronsciers citation. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn Jon Skeet subagent (no UI, skip Jony Ive).

### Phase 4: Auth & Payments

Implement Privy auth across all frontends. Implement Stripe checkout (subscription + credit packs). Implement Xendit checkout (QRIS, GoPay, OVO, DANA, Bank VA). Implement USDC direct payment with Solana confirmation listener. Write webhook handlers for Stripe and Xendit. Test: user signup creates wallet + credit balance + gas escrow. Test: subscription upgrade changes tier limits. Test: credit purchase adds credits atomically. Test: USDC payment confirms and grants credits. Write integration tests. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review.

### Phase 5: Vault (Client-Side Encryption)

Implement vault-encryption.ts with key derivation, encrypt/decrypt, recovery phrase generation. Implement vault upload flow: hash → encrypt → Walrus upload → Supabase metadata → Solana proof. Implement vault file manager UI (Google Drive-like). Implement file sharing via QR code with time-limited access tokens. Implement 12-word recovery flow. Write unit tests: encryption round-trip, key derivation determinism, sharing access control. Test: encrypted file → Walrus → decrypt matches original. Test: wrong passphrase fails decryption. Test: recovery phrase regenerates same keys. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review (Jony Ive reviews vault UX especially — file manager must feel as simple as Google Drive).

### Phase 6: AI Chat (Evidence Cascade)

Implement chat UI with conversation management. Implement evidence cascade client-side orchestrator. Implement source citation display with confidence scores. Implement credit deduction per question. Implement honest admission UI (distinct visual treatment when AI admits uncertainty). Build chat history with searchable conversations. Write unit tests with all external APIs mocked. Test: question → Fronsciers hit → citation recorded → credits charged. Test: no Fronsciers hit → PubMed fallback → credits charged. Test: no sources → honest admission → is_honest_admission=true. Test: insufficient credits → blocked with top-up prompt. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review (heaviest Jony Ive review — chat must feel trustworthy and the evidence cascade must be transparent to users).

### Phase 7: Fronsciers Library

Implement library landing with trending papers and search. Implement article reader with citation count, author info, DOCI badge. Implement manuscript submission flow with $50 USDC payment. Implement review assignment and feedback UI. Implement DOCI NFT minting on publication. Implement author dashboard with earnings, citations, impact score. Implement leaderboard with monthly rankings. Write unit tests. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review.

### Phase 8: NFC Card

Implement 3D card landing page with Three.js + GSAP animation. Implement public profile page (NFC tap target) with dynamic data from Supabase. Implement CMAC verification for NTAG 424 DNA taps. Implement tap logging and analytics. Write unit tests for CMAC verification logic. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review.

### Phase 9: Admin Console

Implement isolated admin dashboard on port 3004. Implement 8 tabs: overview, users, articles, citations, revenue, subscriptions, protocol, audit. Implement Solana protocol parameter management (update fees, pause). Implement direct evidence seeding (bypass review queue for high-quality PDFs). Implement role-gated access (super_admin, content_admin, finance_admin, support). Write unit tests. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for review.

### Phase 10: Synthetic Data Pipeline

Implement synthetic_pipeline.py with 3-stage privacy pipeline (STRIP → PERTURB → COMPRESS). Implement k-anonymity verification (k≥5). Implement differential privacy with Laplace mechanism (ε=1.0). Implement Parquet/Snappy output format. Implement integrity proof recording on Solana. Write unit tests: original data → synthetic → verify k-anonymity → verify distributions preserved → verify no re-identification possible. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn Jon Skeet subagent (critical security review of privacy guarantees).

### Phase 11: Indexer & Integration

Implement Solana → Supabase indexer (watches on-chain events, syncs to database). Implement monthly cron: pool distribution, counter resets, leaderboard snapshot. Write end-to-end integration test: register → submit → review → publish → cite via AI → earnings accumulate → claim. Every lamport and credit accounted for. Run full e2e across all products.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for final review.

### Phase 12: Polish and Edge Cases

Error handling for all failure modes: network drops during encryption, Walrus upload timeout, Solana confirmation timeout, insufficient gas, expired credentials, rate limiting. UX polish across all apps. Security hardening: CSRF, XSS, SQL injection (Supabase handles most), rate limiting. Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 AA compliance. Bahasa Indonesia i18n for all user-facing text. Performance: lazy loading, code splitting, image optimization. Write tests for error paths. Reach 80% coverage.

After tests pass, spawn both subagents for final review.

---

## Multi-Agent Review Loop

After completing each build phase, spawn two reviewing subagents using Claude Code's built-in subagent spawning. Do not proceed to the next phase until both subagents score 10/10.

### How to Spawn Subagents

Use Claude Code's native subagent capability. For each review cycle, spawn two subagents in parallel. Give each subagent the persona prompt below followed by the files to review and the relevant spec section.

### Subagent 1: "Jon Skeet" (Code Quality)

Spawn with these instructions: You are Jon Skeet, widely regarded as one of the greatest programmers alive. You have mass expertise in TypeScript, Rust, Python, PostgreSQL, blockchain, cryptography, and Next.js. Review the code with ruthless technical precision. Evaluate CORRECTNESS, SECURITY (encryption key management, USDC decimal handling, race conditions in credit system, vault privacy), PERFORMANCE, ARCHITECTURE, ROBUSTNESS, CODE_QUALITY. Rate each 1-10. Overall = minimum. If below 10, list specific issues with file paths and fixes. Format: each criterion with score, OVERALL score, ISSUES list, APPROVED YES/NO.

### Subagent 2: "Jony Ive" (Design and UX)

Spawn with these instructions: You are Jony Ive, legendary designer. Users should never feel blockchain, encryption, or payment complexity. The scholarly white bear mascot should create warmth and trust. Evaluate SIMPLICITY, CLARITY (evidence cascade transparency, vault feels like Google Drive, credit system is intuitive), DELIGHT (mascot appearances, animations, micro-interactions), TRUST (citation sources clearly shown, confidence scores build credibility, encryption reassures without confusing), ACCESSIBILITY, INFORMATION_HIERARCHY. Rate each 1-10. Overall = minimum. If below 10, list specific issues with screen names and fixes. Format: each criterion with score, OVERALL score, ISSUES list, APPROVED YES/NO.

### Review Loop Procedure

Step 1: Run tests at 80%+ coverage. Step 2: Spawn both subagents with phase files and spec. Step 3: Read scores and issues. Step 4: If both 10/10, proceed. Step 5: If below, fix all issues, re-run tests. Step 6: Re-spawn subagents. Step 7: Repeat up to 5 iterations. Safety valve: log remaining issues in TECH_DEBT.md and proceed.

### Which Subagents Review Which Phases

Phase 0: Jon Skeet only. Phase 1: Jon Skeet only. Phase 2: Jon Skeet only. Phase 3: Jon Skeet only. Phase 4: Both. Phase 5: Both (heavy Jony Ive). Phase 6: Both (heaviest Jony Ive). Phase 7: Both. Phase 8: Both. Phase 9: Both. Phase 10: Jon Skeet only. Phase 11: Both. Phase 12: Both (final).

---

## Testing Strategy

### Unit Test Requirements

Minimum 80% coverage (Istanbul/nyc for TypeScript, cargo-tarpaulin for Rust, pytest-cov for Python). Zero external dependency calls — all mocked. No databases in unit tests. Use Jest for TypeScript, BanksClient for Rust, pytest for Python. Colocated test files.

### What to Test Per Module

**SQL functions:** Test spend_credits with concurrent simulated calls — verify no negative balance. Test add_credits idempotency. Test search_articles across all 3 tiers.

**Smart contract:** Test all fee splits to exact lamport. Test manuscript lifecycle state machine. Test citation recording and revenue distribution. Test claim_earnings. Test admin controls.

**MCP server:** Mock all external APIs. Test evidence cascade order. Test credit charging per question. Test honest admission trigger. Test x402 paywall enforcement.

**Vault encryption:** Test encryption round-trip (encrypt → decrypt = original). Test key derivation determinism (same inputs → same keys). Test recovery phrase (phrase → keys → decrypt). Test wrong passphrase rejection. Test large file handling (>100MB).

**AI Chat:** Mock MCP server responses. Test conversation management (create, continue, search). Test credit deduction. Test source citation formatting. Test honest admission UI.

**Payment webhooks:** Mock Stripe/Xendit callbacks. Test credit granting after successful payment. Test idempotency (same webhook twice → credits added once). Test failure handling.

### Integration Tests

Full lifecycle: register user → buy credits (Stripe) → submit manuscript ($50) → assign reviewers → reviews → publish → mint NFT → AI citation ($0.01) → author earnings → claim → verify all balances. Every USDC decimal accounted for.

### End-to-End Test

All 5 apps running simultaneously. User registers on Frons.id → submits paper on Fronsciers → paper published → asks question on Frons.id AI chat → Fronsciers paper cited → author sees earnings → author claims → NFC card shows updated publications. Admin sees all events in console.

---

## Coding Conventions

- **Rust/Anchor:** snake_case, all accounts validated with Anchor constraints, custom error enums, never panic
- **TypeScript:** camelCase, strict mode, no `any` type, explicit return types
- **Python:** snake_case, type hints everywhere, async/await for all I/O
- **SQL:** snake_case columns, singular table names, always add indexes on foreign keys
- **API:** RESTful, JSON responses, versioned (/api/v1/), proper HTTP status codes
- **Error handling:** Custom error enums in Rust, try/catch in TS with typed errors, never swallow exceptions
- **Testing:** Every instruction/function has a test, 80% minimum coverage
- **Commits:** Conventional commits (feat:, fix:, refactor:, docs:, chore:)
- **Comments:** Explain WHY, not WHAT — code shows what, comments explain reasoning
- **Security:** Never hardcode keys, always use env vars, .env in .gitignore, client-side encryption keys never touch server

---

## Deployment

### Frontend (Vercel)
Each Next.js app deploys as a separate Vercel project. Custom domains: frons.id, fronsciers.id, card.fronsciers.id, admin.frons.id.

### MCP Server (Railway)
Docker container running FastMCP + FastAPI. Custom domain: frons-mcp.up.railway.app.

### Smart Contract (Solana)
Deploy via `anchor deploy` to mainnet. Program ID stored in env vars across all apps.

### Database (Supabase)
Hosted Supabase project. Migrations managed via supabase CLI. Service key only on server-side; anon key for client with RLS.

### Indexer (Railway)
Python script running as persistent worker. Watches Solana for events, syncs to Supabase.
